There's no existing project in the directory. I'll explain the implementation — you can drop these pieces into your project.

**1. Create `Middleware/ApiExceptionHandler.cs`:**

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Diagnostics;
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;

namespace YourApp.Middleware;

internal sealed class ApiExceptionHandler(ILogger<ApiExceptionHandler> logger)
    : IExceptionHandler
{
    public async ValueTask<bool> TryHandleAsync(
        HttpContext httpContext,
        Exception exception,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken)
    {
        var (statusCode, title) = exception switch
        {
            KeyNotFoundException => (StatusCodes.Status404NotFound, "Not Found"),
            ArgumentException   => (StatusCodes.Status400BadRequest, "Bad Request"),
            InvalidOperationException => (StatusCodes.Status409Conflict, "Conflict"),
            _ => (0, (string?)null)
        };

        if (statusCode == 0)
            return false; // fall through to default 500 handler

        logger.LogWarning(exception, "Handled API exception: {Title}", title);

        httpContext.Response.StatusCode = statusCode;
        await httpContext.Response.WriteAsJsonAsync(new ProblemDetails
        {
            Status = statusCode,
            Title = title,
            Detail = title,          // safe — never use exception.Message
            Instance = httpContext.Request.Path
        }, cancellationToken);

        return true;
    }
}
```

**2. Wire it up in `Program.cs`:**

```csharp
// Services
builder.Services.AddExceptionHandler<ApiExceptionHandler>();
builder.Services.AddProblemDetails();   // ensures unhandled → 500 Problem Details

// Middleware (before app.MapXxx calls)
app.UseExceptionHandler();
app.UseStatusCodePages();
```

**How it works:**

| Exception | Status | Handled by |
|---|---|---|
| `KeyNotFoundException` | 404 | `ApiExceptionHandler` |
| `ArgumentException` | 400 | `ApiExceptionHandler` |
| `InvalidOperationException` | 409 | `ApiExceptionHandler` |
| Anything else | 500 | Built-in `AddProblemDetails()` (no sensitive details) |

The handler returns `false` for unknown exceptions, so the default middleware produces a generic 500 Problem Details response. No `try-catch` needed in endpoints — just `throw` the appropriate exception from your service layer.
